terms.rationale:
**Gen 32:31 (MT) deploys three foundational HB theophany-elements in a single verse: the toponym *Peni'el* (Face-of-El), the *panim el panim* (face-to-face) direct-divine-encounter formula, and the *va-tinatzel nafshi* (and my soul was delivered) survived-theophany clause. The verse is the patriarchal corpus's most-direct claim of a face-to-face encounter with Elohim, and the cross-corpus *panim el panim* formula and the survived-theophany trope it inaugurates are central to HB theophany-theology.**

**(a) The toponym *Peni'el*.** *Peni'el* (פְּנִיאֵל) is a construct-chain: *peni-* (the construct-form of *panim*, *face*) + *El* (the deity-name). The toponym means *Face-of-El*. The in-text etymology at v 31 — *ki-ra'iti Elohim panim el panim* (*for I have seen Elohim face to face*) — makes the toponym's face-of-the-deity meaning explicit. The toponym is a **place-name aetiology**: Ya'aqov names the site after the encounter, following the chapter's wider etiological-naming pattern (*Machanayim* at v 3; *Yisra'el* at v 29; *Peni'el* at v 31).

**The variant form *Penu'el* (פְּנוּאֵל)** appears at the next verse (Gen 32:32, MT) and is the form used in the cross-corpus subsequent material: **Judg 8:8-9** (Gid'on's confrontation with the men of Penu'el on the pursuit of Zevach and Tzalmuna'); **Judg 8:17** (Gid'on's destruction of the *migdal Penu'el* and slaying of the men of the city); **1 Kgs 12:25** (Yerov'am's rebuilding of *Penu'el* alongside *Sh'khem* as one of his two royal-fortification-sites). The two forms (*Peni'el* / *Penu'el*) are dialectal-orthographic variants of the same toponym — preserved side-by-side in adjacent verses of Gen 32 — and are not editorially harmonized. The WoH translation preserves both forms.

**(b) The *panim el panim* formula.** The adverbial-formula *panim el panim* (פָּנִים אֶל־פָּנִים) — *face to face* — is the HB's canonical direct-divine-encounter idiom. Cross-corpus loci:

- **Gen 32:31** (here — Ya'aqov's *ra'iti Elohim panim el panim*);
- **Exod 33:11** (*v-diber YHWH el-Moshe panim el panim ka-asher y-daber ish el-re'ehu* — *and YHWH spoke to Moshe face to face, as a man speaks to his neighbor* — the keystone Mosaic-deployment, the Tent of Meeting context);
- **Deut 5:4** (Moshe at Sinai: *panim b-panim diber YHWH imakhem ba-har mi-tokh ha-esh* — *face to face YHWH spoke with you at the mountain from the midst of the fire* — the variant *panim b-panim* with the *b-* preposition; the Sinai-people-encounter);
- **Deut 34:10** (the closing eulogy of Moshe: *v-lo qam navi od b-Yisra'el k-Moshe asher yeda'o YHWH panim el panim* — *and there has not arisen a prophet since in Yisra'el like Moshe, whom YHWH knew face to face* — the formula as the **defining-characteristic of Mosaic uniqueness**);
- **Judg 6:22** (Gid'on's recognition: *ki ra'iti mal'akh YHWH panim el panim* — *for I have seen the messenger of YHWH face to face*; the *mal'akh*-mediated variant, with Gid'on's fear-of-death the immediate consequence — paralleling Ya'aqov's *va-tinatzel nafshi*);
- **Ezek 20:35** (the eschatological-judgment scene: *v-nishpatti itkhem sham panim el panim*);
- **1 Cor 13:12** NT-reception (*blepomen gar arti di esoptrou en ainigmati, tote de prosōpon pros prosōpon* — Paul's eschatological use, drawing on the HB formula).

The formula names **the most-direct mode** of divine encounter — the antithesis of the **Exod 33:20** *lo yir'ani ha-adam va-chai* (*no man shall see me and live*). The two verses are in apparent contradiction: Exod 33:11 affirms Moshe's *panim el panim* encounter; Exod 33:20 (a few verses later, in the same chapter) declares the impossibility of seeing-the-deity-and-living. The rabbinic-tradition and modern critical readings resolve the tension variously: (i) the *panim el panim* of Exod 33:11 is metaphorical for *intimate communication*, not literal-visual face-of-the-deity; (ii) the two verses derive from different sources or compositional strata (J-or-E vs. P or later); (iii) the contradiction is editorially preserved as paradoxical, marking the limit-of-language for the divine-encounter. **Sarna** *JPS Genesis* 1989 p. 229 reads Gen 32:31 as the patriarchal-equivalent of Moshe's privileged-encounter; **Westermann** *Genesis 12-36* 1985 pp. 523-524 reads the verse as the climax of the wrestling-narrative, with the *panim el panim* + survived-theophany as the **foundational HB instance** of the formula that subsequent theophany-passages will reference. **Hamori** *When Gods Were Men* 2008 treats the chapter as one of the two clearest HB instances of an embodied *'iš*-theophany (the other being Gen 18).

**(c) *Va-tinatzel nafshi* — the survived-theophany clause.** *Va-tinatzel nafshi* (וַתִּנָּצֵל נַפְשִׁי) — *and my soul was delivered* — is the niphal of *natzal* (deliver, rescue, snatch from danger) with *nefesh* (life, soul, self) as the subject. The clause names the **survival of a mortally-dangerous encounter**: Ya'aqov recognizes that he has experienced what the HB elsewhere treats as fatal (seeing the deity), and his *nefesh* has been *delivered* — the verb registers the rescue from a fatal-default-outcome. The clause is structurally parallel to **Judg 6:22-23** (Gid'on: *ahah Adonai YHWH ki al-ken ra'iti mal'akh YHWH panim el panim va-yomer lo YHWH shalom lakh al-tira lo tamut* — *alas, Lord YHWH, for I have seen the messenger of YHWH face to face; and YHWH said to him, peace to you, do not fear, you shall not die* — the deity's reassurance follows Gid'on's recognition); to **Judg 13:22-23** (Manoah after the *mal'akh YHWH* ascends in the flame: *mot namut ki Elohim ra'inu* — *we shall surely die, because we have seen Elohim* — the same fatal-default-outcome assumption; Manoah's wife counters with the *if-the-deity-had-wanted-to-kill-us-he-would-not-have-accepted-our-offering* argument); to **Exod 19:21** (YHWH to Moshe at Sinai: *redah ha'ed ba-am pen-yehersu el-YHWH lir'ot v-nafal mimenu rav* — *go down, warn the people, lest they break through to YHWH to see, and many of them fall*); to **Exod 33:20** (the explicit declaration: *lo tukhal lir'ot et-panai ki lo yir'ani ha-adam va-chai* — *you cannot see my face, for no man shall see me and live*). The survived-theophany trope is foundational HB theology: divine-visibility is fatal-by-default, and the recorded-survivors (Ya'aqov here; Moshe at Exod 33:11 and 34:6-7; the Sinai-people at Deut 5:4; Gid'on at Judg 6:22; Manoah at Judg 13:22; possibly Isaiah at Isa 6:5 — *oy-li ki nidmeiti ki ish-tmei sefatayim anokhi* — *woe is me, for I am undone, for I am a man of unclean lips* — Isaiah's *nidmeiti* registers the same death-default) are recorded as exceptional.

**The patriarchal-theophany cluster.** Gen 32:31 is the patriarchal-corpus's most-explicit survived-theophany verse, but it stands within a wider cluster: **Gen 16:13** (Hagar at the well: *ha-gam halom ra'iti acharei ro'i* — possibly *have I also here seen after he-who-sees-me*, or *have I seen the back of him-who-sees-me* — Hagar's astonishment at having seen-the-deity-and-survived); **Gen 18** (the three visitors at Mamre — the *ish*-theophany, paralleling the Gen 32 *ish*-theophany; see the companion `the-ish-of-penuel-anonymous-wrestler` entry); **Gen 28:17** (Ya'aqov at Bethel: *mah norah ha-maqom ha-zeh* — *how awesome is this place*, the awe-of-a-divine-encounter response without the survival-anxiety articulated). The Gen 32:31 verse is the cluster's most-articulated instance.

**Translation choice.** The WoH renders *Peni'el* (transliterated; the construct-form preserved with the apostrophe-marker to distinguish the toponym from the related noun *peni-*) at v 31; *Penu'el* (the v 32 variant) preserved separately; *face to face* (ASV-baseline) for *panim el panim*; *my life is preserved* (ASV-baseline) for *va-tinatzel nafshi* (the rendering preserves the survival-from-mortal-danger sense without over-translating *nefesh* as *soul* in the modern theological sense). The alternative rendering *my soul was delivered* (preserving *nefesh* literally) is documented as a defensible variant and matches the WoH practice on *nefesh* elsewhere (see the [nefesh-chayah](#nefesh-chayah) entry); the ASV-baseline *my life is preserved* is adopted here for the chapter-baseline.

**Modern scholarly literature.** Sarna *JPS Genesis* 1989 pp. 228-229; Westermann *Genesis 12-36* 1985 pp. 519-524; Wenham *WBC Genesis 16-50* 1994 pp. 295-298; Hamilton *NICOT Genesis 18-50* 1995 pp. 332-336; Speiser *AB Genesis* 1964 pp. 254-258; Alter *The Five Books of Moses* 2004 pp. 181-183; von Rad *Genesis* OTL 1972 pp. 319-322; Hamori *When Gods Were Men: The Embodied God in Biblical and Near Eastern Literature* 2008 (the foundational modern monograph on the embodied-deity-theophany type); Cross *Canaanite Myth and Hebrew Epic* 1973 ch. 1 (the Ugaritic-El intertext for the *Peni'el* toponym); Sommer *The Bodies of God and the World of Ancient Israel* 2009; for the *panim el panim* formula across the Pentateuch: Childs *The Book of Exodus* OTL 1974 pp. 596-597 (on Exod 33:11); Propp *Exodus 19-40* AB 2006 pp. 600-606 (on Exod 33:11 and 33:20). The claim_type is *direct* because (a) the toponym *Peni'el* and its in-text etymology are grammatically explicit; (b) the *panim el panim* formula's cross-corpus distribution is verifiable by lexical search; (c) the *va-tinatzel nafshi* survived-theophany clause is grammatically explicit; (d) the Exod 33:11 / 33:20 tension and the cross-corpus survived-theophany cluster are HB-internal-explicit; (e) the mainstream modern critical reading (Sarna, Westermann, Hamori, Sommer) is documentary; (f) the formula's foundational role in HB theophany-theology is consensus.

**Cross-corpus appliesTo: Gen 33:10 — the Esav-reunion echo.** The v2.31.0 expansion adds **Gen 33:10** to the *appliesTo* — the chapter-33 verse that explicitly echoes the Gen 32:31 *panim el panim* / *va-tinatzel nafshi* formula at the Esav-reunion. Gen 33:10 (MT): *va-yomer Ya'aqov al-na im-na matzati chen b-eyneykha v-laqachta minchati mi-yadi ki al-ken ra'iti panekha kir'ot p'nei Elohim va-tirtzeni* — *and Ya'aqov said, no, I pray, if now I have found favor in your eyes, then receive my present from my hand; forasmuch as I have seen your face, as one sees the face of Elohim, and you have been pleased with me*. The verse redeploys three lexical-components from Gen 32:31: (i) *ra'iti* (qal pf 1cs of *ra'ah* — *I have seen*), the same verb-form used at 32:31 *ki ra'iti Elohim* (*for I have seen Elohim*); (ii) *p'nei Elohim* (construct *panim* + *Elohim*), the same construct used at 32:31 (*Elohim panim el panim*); (iii) *va-tirtzeni* (qal impf 2ms-with-1cs-suffix of *ratzah* — *and you have been pleased with me / accepted me*), structurally parallel to 32:31's *va-tinatzel nafshi* (*and my life is preserved*) — both verbs registering the surviving-of-a-mortally-dangerous-encounter from the encountering-party's perspective. The Gen 33:10 verse is thus the chapter's deliberate **human-counterpart-of-Penuel** echo: Ya'aqov, having survived the night-theophany with the *ish* at Penuel (Gen 32), here survives the dawn-encounter with Esav, and explicitly names Esav's-face as resembling-Elohim's-face. The reading is widely treated in modern critical scholarship as the chapter's structural-keystone: Sarna *JPS Genesis* 1989 pp. 230-231; Westermann *Genesis 12-36* 1985 pp. 526-527; Wenham *WBC Genesis 16-50* 1994 pp. 298-300; Hamilton *NICOT Genesis 18-50* 1995 pp. 343-344; Fokkelman *Narrative Art in Genesis* 1975 pp. 219-222; Alter *Five Books of Moses* 2004 pp. 184-185 (*the simile is a way of saying that he has been afforded a glimpse of forgiveness in his brother's face*); von Rad *Genesis* OTL 1972 p. 325. The translation surface *as one sees the face of Elohim* (ASV-baseline) preserves the lexical-echo intact.

**The polite-courtly-hyperbole register vs. the structural-keystone reading.** A philological note: the *kir'ot p'nei Elohim* construction has been variously read as (i) a **polite-courtly-hyperbole** — *as one sees the face of a god* / *as one sees the face of a noble* — comparable to the ANE court-language register in which a king's audience is described in deity-language (Speiser *AB Genesis* 1964 pp. 259-260 favors this reading, glossing as *as one sees the face of a king*; cf. the *Elohim*-as-judges/rulers semantic-range at Exod 21:6, 22:7-8 in some readings); or (ii) the **structural-keystone-echo** of the Penuel-encounter — the chapter's deliberate cross-reference to 32:31, with *Elohim* in its full divine sense. The Speiser polite-hyperbole reading and the Sarna/Westermann/Alter structural-echo reading are not strictly exclusive — the chapter could be doing both at once — and most modern commentators treat the structural-echo as the dominant register with the polite-hyperbole as a possible secondary-resonance. The WoH translation preserves *the face of Elohim* (capitalized-construct following the WoH *Elohim*-treatment), foregrounding the structural-echo reading without precluding the polite-hyperbole alternative; both readings are documented in commentary.
